Roby, §g 614, 615, suggests that this form of the infinitivo arose thus: the ordinary passive suffix r, in the form er, was added to the active inf., whose final ἒ took the form of i before er. Then the r would be dropt because of its ill sound after another r (Roby‚ ξ 185) and ie contracted to i. Thus amare-er, amar-ier, amaria, amari. This form in -ier is occasionally found in poets of the classical period, e.g. Verg. Aen. 11. 242 farier ,· Hor. Odes, 4, 11, 8 sparyier.
